name: 3,5-difluorobenzoic acid

As there are two fluorine atoms, this effect can be additive. - Carboxylic acid group (COOH): Introduces strong hydrogen bonding which greatly increases the melting point due to significantly increased intermolecular forces. Given this, we might estimate the effects as follows (these estimates would need to be consistent with literature values for similar compounds, but as an example): - Each fluorine could add approximately 20 degrees Celsius due to increased dipole interactions and the rigidity they add to the benzene ring. - The carboxylic acid group could add approximately 100 degrees Celsius due to the potential for strong hydrogen bonding and extended dimerization that the carboxyl group can undergo. Combining these effects, added onto the base melting point of benzene, gives us an estimated melting point for 3,5-difluorobenzoic acid.
